C8_Notes: All airport control was made by federal and state public authorities. However, the mayor closed the bus station in 24.03, and the bus station received several international travellers from Paraguay/ Bolivia, and travellers from other states of Brazil.  The bus station was closed until 28.03 (https://www.midiamax.com.br/cotidiano/2020/na-rodoviaria-de-campo-grande-passageiros-com-sintomas-de-coronavirus-devem-passar-por-triagem) when it was reopened but with screening measures on inter-state passengers.

There is a municipal sanitary barrier in place since April 24; it is not targeted at international travel, however.     The following restrictions have been in place in Vitoria, although they were not determined by the city administration:    The Vitoria Airport was open as usual and had no screening policy in place until April 6.     According to the media, the airport screening policy is based on recommendations from the WHO and national guidance from the Ministry of Health and ANVISA (National Agency of Sanitary Vigilance). The airport administration also lies with the federal government, which could lead one to believe this is a federal policy. However, the latest ANVISA nation-wide recommendation has discouraged screening based on temperature measurement and the Vitoria policy seems to be implemented by the Secretariat of Health (SESA) of the State of Espirito Santo.     For the policy's purposes, the agency borrowed temperature measurement equipment from a private engineering firm through the State Secretariat of Science, Technology, Innovation and Professional Education (SECTI). The screening is carried out by one doctor, one nurse and three nursing technicians with support of members of the fire department.     In regard to the Port of Vitoria, differently from the airport, it was fully closed to foreign crew members for 30 days from March 26. On May 7, after arrivals had resumed, there has a confirmed COVID case of a crew member. He has been previously tested, however, in Rio de Janeiro, although the positive test results only came out when the ship had already arrived in Vitoria. All other crew members were subsequently screened (tested) in the Port due to his case. It appears that, to this moment, there is no general screening policy for all international crew arrivals in place. The Port claims that it is following federal guidance from ANVISA, which discourages temperature measurement.     Sources: https://movimentoonline.com.br/home/2020/04/13/coronavirus-camera-que-mede-temperatura-e-utilizada-em-passageiros-que-chegam-no-aeroporto-de-vitoria/, https://www.agazeta.com.br/es/gv/coronavirus-camera-termografica-e-usada-no-aeroporto-de-vitoria-0420, https://www.folhavitoria.com.br/geral/noticia/04/2020/tripulantes-estrangeiros-estao-proibidos-de-desembarcar-nos-portos-capixabas-por-30-dias, https://www.agazeta.com.br/es/cotidiano/navio-atracado-no-porto-de-vitoria-registra-caso-de-coronavirus-0520ent, https://g1.globo.com/es/espirito-santo/noticia/2020/04/24/prefeitura-instala-barreira-sanitaria-na-rodoviaria-de-vitoria-para-evitar-avanco-do-coronavirus.ghtml

H1_Notes: There is a campaign in place, with an official website (https://coronavirus.palmas.to.gov.br/), posts on social media (@cidadepalmas on Instagram and Twitter) and a WhatsApp account to inform citizens and answer to their questions.     The first social media post was made on March 13. The campaign even includes posts using local jargon to raise awareness, and the Mayor's office Twitter name was changed to include "#FiqueEmCasa", which means "Stay Home".  In the neighborhoods with the most COVID19 cases, there was an in-person educational campaign. Those who left their houses were instructed to stay at home, and if they needed to leave, in cases of extreme need, use safety measures, such as the use of a mask and the use of gel alcohol, in addition to hand and object hygiene rules.  Source: http://www.portalstylo.com.br/noticia-1508566097-campanhas-educativas-nas-quadras-com-maior-incidencia-de-casos-da-covid-19

C8_Notes: Passengers arriving from locations with Covid-19 community transmission must undergo screening procedures, with temperature measurement, and testing, at the road, port and airport terminals.    Link: https://web.archive.org/web/20200524130110/http://www.secom.ba.gov.br/2020/03/152898/Entenda-as-medidas-de-combate-ao-coronavirus-na-Bahia.html    "Os passageiros oriundos de localidades onde ocorre transmissão comunitária da Covid-19 deverão se submeter a procedimentos de triagem, com medição de temperatura, e testagem, nos terminais de transporte rodoviário, portuário e aeroportuário, no momento do desembarque ou em postos específicos para esse fim. Foram instalados postos avançados na BR-116, BR-101 e na BR-242, que ligam a Bahia ao centro-oeste do país. Caminhões e ônibus são parados para que a medição da temperatura dos passageiros seja realizada. Nos casos de quadro clínico sugestivo de coronavírus, o passageiro terá amostra respiratória coletada, receberá Equipamento de Proteção Individual (EPI) e será monitorado pela Autoridade Sanitária local.

H1_Notes: There has been a state-wide information campaign in social media (Instagram and Facebook), with posts and engagement in live videos. There were also press conferences and ads in the traditional media. The first Instagram post raising awareness about preventive measures in the state government's account (@govmatogrosso) was on March 30, which I considered the start date of this policy.     On May 6, Governor Mauro Mendes was considered the governor who devoted the most time to address Covid in his profile. Of the total of 495 posts since March 1, he reserved 74% to alert the state population about the health crisis (source below).    In the city of Rondonopolis, in the end of April, sound-equipped cars also circulated in neighborhoods to spread information and orient citizens on preventive measures in their homes. However, it appears to be a city government measure. C2_Notes: (Fortaleza Official Gazette, 19/04/2020 - edict no. 14.651/2020): Article 1. C2_Notes: On 19 April 2020, the state government of Goiás published a new decree extending the situation of emergency and prolonging some measures such as suspension of interstate and intercity transport, cancellation of public and private events, schools and university closures, and ban on public gatherings.
